[normal]Evidence from the BELMAS Structural Reform Research Programme funded study:
[normal]‘New Relations between Local Authorities and Schools’
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Executive Summary[bold]Academisation has changed the responsibilities and functions of local authorities
[normal] (LAs)
[normal] in resp
[normal]ect of their work with schools, yet they retain significant statutory responsibility for fair access to schooling, the needs of vulnerable children, school improvement and performance, and advocacy for parents, families and children. Their ability to act u
[normal]pon these responsibilities is affected by financial loss as schools convert to academies and central government cuts funding. 
[normal]The resultant climate is competitive, and in some cases, combative.
[normal]This paper reports on findings of case studies 
[normal]of
[normal] four 
[normal]LAs
[normal] wit
[normal]hin one region. Three of the authorities attempted to mitigate competition within the market-led environment, whereas one embraced it. 
[normal]The findings from the project of relevance to this project are divided into two themes: 1) 
[normal]Statutory responsibilities of
[normal] LAs and reduced financial resources
[normal], and 2) 
[normal]Confusion in functions and responsibilities
[normal] of LAs.
[normal]Even though academisation promotes school autonomy, LAs remain statutorily responsible for s
[normal]ome of the operations of academies, 
[normal](for example,
[normal] 
[normal]statutory assessment of SEN and the prosecution of non-attendees at school
[normal])
[normal]. While responsibilities for vulnerable children and many other serious concerns and issues come to the local authority, limited fi
[normal]nancial and human resources can cause significant oversights. A core 
[normal]function for the LA is 
[normal]the capacity to act 
[normal]on all concerns and issues that are brought to it by stakeholders
[normal]. 
[normal]Respondents from the four case studies all reported some element of confusion in respect of their responsibilities to schools. There are responsibilities enshrined in the statutes themselves that have not changed, against which Ofsted 
[normal]inspect
[normal] local authori
[normal]ties, yet different messages 
[normal]about school autonomy 
[normal]emerge from the Department for Education. 
[normal]These ambiguities are exacerbated when schools are transitioning to academy status, and also impact upon an LA’s capacity to offer a stable 
[normal]set of
[normal] service
[normal]s for cru
[normal]cial functions like school improvement
[normal]. 
[normal]Conclusion[bold]This research suggests that a market economy of schooling and services to schools impacts upon local authorities’ capacity to meet the needs of disadvantaged children and young people. LAs need the financ
[normal]ial and human resources to respond to the issues that come to them. As inequalities within society increase, there will be greater demand placed upon LAs to respond to the needs of children.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There is
[normal] a lack of clarity around role and
[normal] responsibility in the interactions betwee
[normal]n schools and local authorities
[normal],
[normal] and also 
[normal]within 
[normal]external relationships
[normal].
[normal] While a simple solution to the ambiguit
[normal]ies
[normal] may appear to be more clearly defining lines of accountability, I think there is a deeper problem 
[normal]to be resolved. Current policies impacting upon the education and care of children emphasise competition, including the academies programme, forcing school
[normal]s and LAs to compete for custom
[normal] and authority
[normal], 
[normal]work
[normal]ing
[normal] against co-operati
[normal]on
[normal] or community engagement. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The expansion of the academies programme 
[normal]since 2010 has resulted in a profound reconfiguration of the responsibilities and functions of local authorities in respect of the
[normal]ir
[normal] work 
[normal]with 
[normal]schools. 
[normal]Through
[normal] 
[normal]The Academies Act
[normal] (2010)
[normal] and 
[normal]The 
[normal]Schools White Paper
[normal] (2010) 
[normal]governing and management bodies of academies have new responsibilities that previously had been responsib
[normal]ilities within
[normal] the
[normal] local authority
[normal], including 
[normal]greater school-level control over finances and expenditure
[normal]. 
[normal]Yet Local 
[normal]Authorities
[normal] (LAs)
[normal] still retain important responsibilities in respect of schooling including:
[normal]•
[normal]              
[normal]Ensuring there is fair access to schooling
[normal]•
[normal]              
[normal]Supporting vulnerable children
[normal]•
[normal]              
[normal]Improving the performance of schools and ensuring high standards  
[normal]•
[normal]              
[normal]Using their de
[normal]mocratic mandate to advocate for parents, families and children 
[normal](DfE, 2010; Parish, Baxter and Sandals, 2012). 
[normal]The capacity of LAs to enact these responsibilities
[normal] is
[normal] affected by significant funding cuts to their formula grants (Stabe &amp; Jones, 2011), but 
[normal]also financial loss as schools convert to academies. A
[normal]cademisation 
[normal]has resulted in
[normal] pro
[normal]found
[normal] change
[normal]s to
[normal] how 
[normal]LA
[normal]s recognise and enact responsibilities for disadvantaged children in 
[normal]academy 
[normal]schools, 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]changes in financing have
[normal] also affected how local authori
[normal]ties relate to maintained schools. Furthermo
[normal]re, the promotion of autonomous
[normal] school
[normal]s has created a competitive 
[normal]environment 
[normal]that works against the best interests of disadvantaged children, making the job of the local authority to ensure the needs of the most
[normal] vulnerable are met much more difficult. 
[normal]An LA Senior Manager
[normal] with strategic responsibility for services to schools 
[normal]claimed that 
[normal]within her LA 
[normal]where 44% of schools are academies, 
[normal]relationships between schools had become “combative”
[normal] as a result of competition.  
[normal]Different 
[normal]LAs
[normal] have trialled different solutions to changes in their resource, but within four 
[normal]recent 
[normal]case studies
[normal] of LAs
[normal] each had made immense moves away from statutory provision as a norm. Of the four 
[normal]LAs
[normal] only one fully embr
[normal]aced a competitive market model to achieve its statutory responsibility to the social good, whereas the other local authorities have differently attempted to mitigate the challenges of a competitive environment so they may enact this responsibility. This h
[normal]as been through the following mechanisms:
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Holding onto a limited statutory provision (although in light of recent funding cuts this is unlikely to continue)
[normal];
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Community and stakeholder engagement;
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Utilising business structures founded on principles of coope
[normal]ration and mutuality.
[normal]1.1 Evidential basis of the report[bold]This r
[normal]eport 
[normal]draws upon findings from the ‘New Relations between Local Authorities and Schools’ study to 
[normal]present evidence 
[normal]that addresses the terms of reference of this select committee inquiry in respect of the functions and responsibilities of local authorities. The report presents findings 
[normal]from this study 
[normal]that 
[normal]addresses 
[normal]t
[normal]he functions and responsibilities in relation to acad
[normal]emies and free schools of local authorities operating between the Secretary o
[normal]f State and individual schools, and considers the significance of these findings for determining
[normal] 
[normal]what these functions
[normal] and responsibilities should be. 
[normal]The study has focused upon four 
[normal]LAs
[normal] from within a single region looking at how their relationships with schools have changed as a result of structural reform in the schooling sector. 
